11. Decommissioning and disposal

Decommissioning Processes and Relations

All equipment has a useful life span and at some point will need to be retired or replaced. Sometimes the equipment will need to be removed from service due to wear and tear or failure, while other times it may be due to obsolescence due to changes to business needs or technology. Additionally, there are costs associated with running old equipment. These costs range from a higher rate of failures to lost productivity and higher resource usage compared to newer technologies or efficiency.

Reasons for decommissioning:

  • Wear and tear, failures
    • equipment maintenance costs
    • increased risk of failure due to the age of the equipment
  • Technology advancements and obsolescence
    • Obsolescence due to the changing technological landscape
    • Obsolescence due to end of support, or end of support contracts, or reaching manufacturer end-of-life (EOL)

Various business processes can be used to monitor equipment and evaluate if decommissioning is needed and how it is to be conducted. Monitoring the current state of equipment can be part of the Risk Management monitoring processes. Additionally, risk assessments can be conducted on the decommissioning and disposal aspects of the equipment life cycle. Decommissioning is also part of the IT Lifecycle Management process. Information security management informs the risks and threats to the information associated with the equipment. In short:

  • Risk Management
    • Evaluating threats and risks associated with aging equipment
    • Evaluating threats and risks associated with decommissioning and disposal
    • Evaluating the process and procedures for decommissioning and disposal
      • for example to ensure the CIA is protected before, during, and after the activities: CIA during system upgrade, and required steps to ensure that chain of custody on information is not lost when removing and disposing of old systems.
  • IT Lifecycle Management:
    • Associated costs and procedures of decommissioning and disposal are part of the process
  • Information Security Management:
    • Ensuring compliance with policies and implementation and effectiveness of controls that were identified via the Risk Management process.
    • Inventory management: identification, classification, and organization of assets and information
    • Incident management and response, in case of breach of process or controls, or unexpected events

Common decommissioning steps may be as follows:

  • Discover
    • Define scope, Set budget, Set timetable, Identify stakeholders, select a project manager, select suppliers and service providers, create inventory of assets, Technology dependency map
    • Key questions to answer: Can hardware be re-used? What is lost and needs to be replaced? What are the knock-on effects of the change?
  • Implementation
    • Setup new systems, backups and replication, perform the migration
    • Testing
    • Cutover
      • Big bang, or Phased
  • Disposal
    • recycle, reuse, or safely dispose (sanitize)
    • Securely destroy
  • Other considerations:
    • Agreements and service contracts
    • Software licenses
    • Residual data

Decommissioning and Disposal of Storage Media

All information stored must be classified, inventoried, and tracked. This requires explicit policies and controls to be set and enforced on all mediums where the information is stored and transmitted. Therefore information security risks extend beyond the useful life of media and devices.

  • Example of a typical incident is when servers have failed HDDs that are going to be replaced under warranty by an onsite technician sent by the vendor. The defective media is to be returned to the manufacturer (the technician will install new drives and take the defective ones with them). What needs to be done for every incident?
    • Attempt to wipe the media before they are removed from the premises. What if the failed disks cannot be wiped due to the failure? May require additional equipment (software and hardware) to ensure all data is destroyed, and also needs different equipment for different types of media (SATA vs SAS vs FC interfaces for HDDs or SSDs, or PCIe for some SSDs, or proprietary FC cards for some SAN devices, etc).
    • Destroy the defective media and pay for new media, or sign "media retention" contracts with the vendor (has its associated costs or either buying the media every time or signing a contract with the vendor before the incident)
    • Reduce risk by using encryption for all data at rest, so all information in the failed disks is already strongly encrypted (This option requires the organization to have provisioned and implemented this before the incident)

See the Bleeping Computer reporting in Aug 2024 titled "Audit finds notable security gaps in FBI's storage media management" for an example of real-world implications
Or this one from the U.S. Department of Justice Office of the Inspector General for the same report: "DOJ OIG Releases Management Advisory Memorandum of Concerns Identified with the FBI’s Inventory Management and Disposition Procedures of Electronic Storage Media"

Controls for Storage Media

The term used for non-destructive removal of sensitive information is referred to as sanitization. There are many guidelines and procedures available. Some information sources are:

  • Canadian Center for Cyber Security: IT media sanitization (ITSP.40.006): https://www.cyber.gc.ca/en/guidance/it-media-sanitization-itsp40006
  • NIST: SP 800-88r1 - Guidelines for Media Sanitization: https://csrc.nist.gov/publications/detail/sp/800-88/rev-1/final
  • ISO/IEC 27040: https://www.iso.org/standard/44404.html
  • Canadian Version is CAN/CSA-ISO/IEC 27040:18: https://www.scc.ca/en/standardsdb/standards/29695

Sanitization

In general sanitization process uses various techniques to make information non-recoverable, so the media is left in a reusable condition. Sanitation tools and processes are media-dependent, and one tool cannot be applied to all mediums and technologies. As an example sanitizing HDDs and NAND Flash SSDs requires different tools and methods. Therefore there are costs associated with sanitization. Costs can range from just time and labour to special equipment and software. For example, it may take many hours to sanitize data on all platters of a large HDD (high cost in time and labour) while SAN HDDs may use proprietary interfaces and formats that cannot be easily connected to standard hardware and software to perform the sanitization, and the vendor may offer proprietary tools or services specific to their product.

Some medical sanitization methods include:

  • Data shredding:
    • A software solution to write over specific regions of the disk where the file was stored to make any traces of it unrecoverable.
    • Faster, but requires the file system to be accessible and all available data to be inventoried on the media
    • Only works for magnetic storage media (such as tapes and HDDs), will not work on SSD
  • Low-Level Rewriting:
    • using software to write random patterns to all sectors of a disk
    • Takes longer, but does not care for the file system. Uses low-level access to the storage media blocks and sectors
    • Only works for magnetic storage media, will not work on SSDs
  • Proprietary software or feature:
    • Some enterprise-grade servers and storage may have the option to use proprietary processes in software or firmware to perform media sanitization on the device for decommissioning
    • Only applies to supported systems and specific devices
    • may require higher initial investment or additional charges to use
  • Degaussing media:
    • special machine that produces very high magnetic fields, in order to disrupt and wipe the data on magnetic storage. Degaussing may be less effective on modern HDDs as they have better protection against magnetic fields, and require increasingly more powerful magnetic fields to be effective.
    • Does not work on anything but magnetic media.

None of the above methods work on modern SSDs and flash media. SSD storage is fundamentally different from traditional hard drives. The sectors and blocks in an SSD do not correspond to the underlying memory cells where the bits are stored. This is due to the fact that most SSD storage media (NAND Flash) have limited write cycles for each cell, and controllers perform "wear levelling" operations where the logical block numbers are moved on each write to different cells in order to distribute write cycles to avoid premature failures. Data shredding will not work, because the technique relies on rewriting to specific blocks and sectors on a disk. Low-level rewriting may not work on some SSD drives depending on the underlying technology, due to under-provisioning and caching inside an SSD. Degausing will never work, because NAND Flash uses electro-static charge for storing bits rather than magnetic orientation.

The existing solutions are not universal. Different manufacturers and models from the same manufacturer may require different processes for sanitization. Here are some methods for sanitizing SSD:

  • Using manufacturer-provided secure erase utilities:
    • will only work with specifically supported media. Some examples include Samsung Magician, Intel Memory and Storage Tool, Crucial Storage Executive, WD Dashboard, etc.
  • Using specific built-in commands on supported SSDs via an operating system or software
    • sometimes may be referred to as "ATA Secure Erase Command", and different products may behave differently
      • It can range from rewriting every cell to just deleting the controller table of contents in the controller memory effectively "factory resetting" the drive, and the drive "forgets" the locations of where the blocks are stored inside the NAND chips
    • Very much dependent on the underlying specific model of the device and what features are supported
  • Encryption is not the same as Sanitization, but has many benefits, the most apparent in modern systems. We will discuss this a little later.

Destruction

If the cost of sanitization is too high due to costs or complexity, then destruction may be an option. I have witnessed many methods of destruction. For a small number of drives sometimes something as simple as using a drill to put several holes in a disk may suffice, while for many drives (it can be in several hundreds to thousands for a single large SAN device there are companies that supply special equipment designed for shredding drives onsite. The goal is to "securely destroy", so the formal processes for compliance with frameworks may require keeping inventory and records of proof of destruction.

Encryption

The premise is simple: encrypt all "data at rest" (before it is written to the underlying storage medium). Encryption is supposed to protect the data even if threat sources get hold of the physical media. The cost of encryption has been reduced due to technological improvements reducing overhead associated with encryption, therefore there is very little reason to not employ encryption. Depending on the threat model and level of sensitivity of data, encryption may eliminate the need for sanitization.

An example of this can be as simple as having Microsoft Windows Bit-Locker and TPM enabled on a laptop or desktop (must ensure the device comes with TPM onboard). Microsoft Windows typically provides a recovery key as a backup and the encryption key is stored in the TMP. In case the device needs to be decommissioned, the IT technician only needs to remove/destroy the recovery keys, and reset the TPM module (erase the key), and the system will become unrecoverable. The storage then can be formatted and a new OS installed, or the device can be sent back to the vendor or for recycling.

This principle can be extended to all storage mediums, including SSDs and even removable media. Servers and SANs can optionally use "self-encrypting" drives, where the drive will automatically negotiate a key with a specific storage controller inside the server or SAN when added to the system, and all data is encrypted on all individual disks. If the disk is removed and inserted in a different server or SAN storage, the data inside the disk cannot be read because the encryption key resides in the previous machine. Additionally most servers and SANs can add additional and separate encryption on logical volumes or on each object (in the case of object storage), and therefore the encrypted bits that are stored in a physical disk were already encrypted. In this case, data sanitization is not required.

Residual Data and Risks

Residual data refers to information that is left behind, sometimes even after sanitization. Generally sanitizing or encrypting a standard storage device is not a challenge. The challenge lies in non-standard and proprietary systems where storage is not their primary function or in their description. These systems can be any IoT, network switches and routers, printers, appliances or anything that may store information internally in order to function or provide additional features. Residual information in these kinds of equipment is difficult to discover and may require specific knowledge about the interworking of the device to be able to classify and inventory information.

Some examples of such systems and information:

  • Decommissioned network printer model may include storage media inside that had stored documents and print-jobs
  • Switches and routers storing configured IP and network route tables, and other infrastructure-related information
  • Appliances storing credentials and encryption keys (for example a Cisco router has admin credentials stored)
  • Storage drives in servers that have been wiped, but the management computer (HP iLO, Dell iDRAC, etc) still contains company information, license keys, and user accounts and credentials, even federation access tokens (allowing remote management of all servers)
